Note:
GEO_COORDINATE - Tier 1 typed geographic position

A geographic coordinate identifies a point on (or near) the Earth's surface
by latitude (north-south angular position), longitude (east-west angular
position), and altitude (height relative to the reference datum's ellipsoid).
The reference datum (WGS84, NAD83, etc.) anchors the abstract angular
coordinate frame to a specific geophysical model.

This file provides the `GeoCoordinate` value type and its constructors,
validators, and accessors. Datum-specific transformations and conversions
between coordinate-reference-systems (ECEF, ECI, LLH, ENU, NED) live in
coordinate_reference_system.runa.

DESIGN

A GeoCoordinate stores latitude and longitude as decimal degrees (the most
common interchange format), altitude in meters above the datum ellipsoid,
and a Datum tag indicating the reference frame. WGS84 is the default and
is overwhelmingly the most common case (used by GPS, ICAO charts, most
GIS data); other datums are supported for legacy and regional applications.

The latitude/longitude format follows ISO 6709:2008 sign conventions:
  latitude:  negative south, positive north,  range [-90, +90]
  longitude: negative west,  positive east,   range [-180, +180]
  altitude:  meters above the ellipsoid (positive up)

Validation procedures enforce these ranges; constructors clamp out-of-range
values to the canonical representation when called via geo_coord_create_clamped,
and reject (return zeroed) when called via geo_coord_create_strict.

REPRESENTATION

We store decimal degrees rather than radians for the latitude/longitude
fields because callers most often consume these from GPS/GIS sources in
degrees, and the conversion to radians at the consumer (great-circle
distance, projection) is a single multiply. The Angle-typed counterpart
in units_of_measure.runa is intentionally separate: Angle is dimensionless
in the geometric sense, while GeoCoordinate is a domain-specific structure
that always carries an Earth-relative meaning.

DEPENDENCIES

  - compiler/frontend/primitives/units/units_of_measure.runa for Length-typed
    altitude when a typed accessor is requested.

CITATIONS

  - ISO 6709:2008 - Standard representation of geographic point location by
    coordinates. Sign conventions and range definitions.
  - WGS84 (NIMA TR8350.2, Department of Defense World Geodetic System 1984,
    third edition amendment 1 (2000)) - the default ellipsoid and datum.
  - GeoJSON (RFC 7946) - JSON-style geographic feature interchange; uses
    [longitude, latitude, altitude?] ordering with WGS84.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/units/units_of_measure.runa" as Units

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - Datum enumeration
Note: ============================================================================
Note: A datum specifies the reference frame for a geographic coordinate. It
Note: combines an ellipsoid (Earth-shape model), a positioning of that
Note: ellipsoid relative to the center of mass of the Earth, and an
Note: orientation. Two coordinates with the same lat/lon but different
Note: datums refer to different physical points (typically separated by
Note: tens to hundreds of meters depending on the datums involved).
Note: Supported datums:
Note:   WGS84    - World Geodetic System 1984. Default. GPS reference frame.
Note:   NAD83    - North American Datum 1983. US/Canada modern reference.
Note:   ETRS89   - European Terrestrial Reference System 1989. EU reference.
Note:   ITRF2014 - International Terrestrial Reference Frame 2014. Geodetic.
Note:   ITRF2020 - International Terrestrial Reference Frame 2020. Geodetic.
Note:   NAD27    - North American Datum 1927. Legacy US/Canada.
Note:   OSGB36   - Ordnance Survey Great Britain 1936. UK national grid.
Note:   Tokyo    - Tokyo Datum (Bessel 1841 in Japan). Legacy Japan.

Type Datum is:
    | WGS84
    | NAD83
    | ETRS89
    | ITRF2014
    | ITRF2020
    | NAD27
    | OSGB36
    | Tokyo
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - GeoCoordinate structure
Note: ============================================================================
Note: A point on (or near) the Earth's surface. Latitude and longitude are
Note: decimal degrees. Altitude is meters above the datum's ellipsoid. The
Note: datum_index field stores the Datum tag as an integer for stage1
Note: compatibility (0=WGS84, 1=NAD83, ..., 7=Tokyo).

Type called "GeoCoordinate":
    latitude_degrees as Float
    longitude_degrees as Float
    altitude_meters as Float
    datum_index as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Datum tag integer encoding
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pure procedures that map a Datum value to its integer encoding. The
Note: integer is what we store in GeoCoordinate.datum_index because stage1
Note: enum values do not yet have first-class equality.

Process called "datum_index_wgs84" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "datum_index_nad83" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "datum_index_etrs89" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "datum_index_itrf2014" returns Integer:
    Return 3
End Process

Process called "datum_index_itrf2020" returns Integer:
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "datum_index_nad27" returns Integer:
    Return 5
End Process

Process called "datum_index_osgb36" returns Integer:
    Return 6
End Process

Process called "datum_index_tokyo" returns Integer:
    Return 7
End Process

Process called "datum_name_from_index" takes idx as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning:
        Map the integer datum tag back to its canonical short name for
        serialization (ISO 6709, WKT, EPSG style references).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Single switch on the integer. Returns "Unknown" for any value
        outside [0, 7] so the caller can detect corruption.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compiles to a branch ladder of compares. Suitable for the cold
        path (printing, serialization). For hot lookups callers should
        cache the resulting string.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Out-of-range indices return a sentinel rather than reading
        a table out of bounds.
    @End Security_Scope
    If idx is equal to 0:
        Return "WGS84"
    End If
    If idx is equal to 1:
        Return "NAD83"
    End If
    If idx is equal to 2:
        Return "ETRS89"
    End If
    If idx is equal to 3:
        Return "ITRF2014"
    End If
    If idx is equal to 4:
        Return "ITRF2020"
    End If
    If idx is equal to 5:
        Return "NAD27"
    End If
    If idx is equal to 6:
        Return "OSGB36"
    End If
    If idx is equal to 7:
        Return "Tokyo"
    End If
    Return "Unknown"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - GeoCoordinate constructors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "geo_coord_create" takes lat_degrees as Float, lon_degrees as Float, alt_meters as Float, datum_idx as Integer returns GeoCoordinate:
    @Reasoning:
        Primary constructor. Stores raw values without range checks. Callers
        responsible for plausibility checks via geo_coord_is_valid. This
        permissive constructor is the right choice for ingest paths where
        caller-supplied data is later validated en bloc rather than per-row.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Default-construct the GeoCoordinate and write all four fields.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four stores. No allocation. Stage1 returns the struct by value
        through the standard SSE2 return-register convention.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Does not interpret the inputs - latitudes outside [-90, 90]
        will be stored as-is. Use geo_coord_create_strict if validation
        is required at construction time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to lat_degrees
    Set c.longitude_degrees to lon_degrees
    Set c.altitude_meters to alt_meters
    Set c.datum_index to datum_idx
    Return c
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_create_wgs84" takes lat_degrees as Float, lon_degrees as Float, alt_meters as Float returns GeoCoordinate:
    Note: Convenience overload defaulting datum to WGS84 (datum_index 0).
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to lat_degrees
    Set c.longitude_degrees to lon_degrees
    Set c.altitude_meters to alt_meters
    Set c.datum_index to 0
    Return c
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_create_strict" takes lat_degrees as Float, lon_degrees as Float, alt_meters as Float, datum_idx as Integer returns GeoCoordinate:
    @Reasoning:
        Validating constructor. Returns a default GeoCoordinate (all-zeros,
        WGS84) when any input is out of range. The strict variant is the
        right choice for user-facing inputs (web forms, command-line tools)
        where bad data should produce a recognizable failure value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Check latitude in [-90, 90], longitude in [-180, 180]. Altitude is
        unbounded (the deepest mariana trench is ~ -11000 m, the highest
        atmospheric altitudes used for HALO operations are ~ +30000 m, and
        space missions go far beyond, so we do not impose a range). On
        rejection return an all-zero default rather than a sentinel value
        because zero-zero is a valid coordinate (in the Gulf of Guinea, the
        "Null Island" coordinate) and callers are expected to invoke
        geo_coord_is_valid to distinguish.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four compares, four stores. The hot path is taken when input is
        in range, which is most cases.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Rejects out-of-range latitudes/longitudes with a sentinel
        value rather than aborting the process.
    @End Security_Scope
    If lat_degrees is greater than 90.0:
        Let zero be a value of type GeoCoordinate
        Set zero.latitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.longitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.altitude_meters to 0.0
        Set zero.datum_index to 0
        Return zero
    End If
    If lat_degrees is less than 0.0 minus 90.0:
        Let zero be a value of type GeoCoordinate
        Set zero.latitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.longitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.altitude_meters to 0.0
        Set zero.datum_index to 0
        Return zero
    End If
    If lon_degrees is greater than 180.0:
        Let zero be a value of type GeoCoordinate
        Set zero.latitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.longitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.altitude_meters to 0.0
        Set zero.datum_index to 0
        Return zero
    End If
    If lon_degrees is less than 0.0 minus 180.0:
        Let zero be a value of type GeoCoordinate
        Set zero.latitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.longitude_degrees to 0.0
        Set zero.altitude_meters to 0.0
        Set zero.datum_index to 0
        Return zero
    End If
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to lat_degrees
    Set c.longitude_degrees to lon_degrees
    Set c.altitude_meters to alt_meters
    Set c.datum_index to datum_idx
    Return c
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - GeoCoordinate validators and accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "geo_coord_is_valid" takes c as GeoCoordinate returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Check that the coordinate is in the canonical range. Used after
        permissive construction to confirm caller-supplied data is well-
        formed. Returns 1 (true) when valid and 0 (false) when invalid.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Check latitude in [-90, 90] and longitude in [-180, 180]. Altitude
        is intentionally not range-checked.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four floating-point compares, branch on the AND. The compiler may
        fold these into a fused conditional move sequence.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope
    If c.latitude_degrees is greater than 90.0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If c.latitude_degrees is less than 0.0 minus 90.0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If c.longitude_degrees is greater than 180.0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If c.longitude_degrees is less than 0.0 minus 180.0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_latitude" takes c as GeoCoordinate returns Float:
    Return c.latitude_degrees
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_longitude" takes c as GeoCoordinate returns Float:
    Return c.longitude_degrees
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_altitude_meters" takes c as GeoCoordinate returns Float:
    Return c.altitude_meters
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_altitude_length" takes c as GeoCoordinate returns Length:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the altitude as a typed Length value, enabling participation
        in dimensional-analysis arithmetic without manual unit boilerplate.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Wrap the meters field via length_in_meters.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One store and one return-by-value of the wrapped Length.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc length_in_meters from Units with c.altitude_meters
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_datum_index" takes c as GeoCoordinate returns Integer:
    Return c.datum_index
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_datum_name" takes c as GeoCoordinate returns String:
    Return datum_name_from_index(c.datum_index)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Latitude / longitude normalization
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "normalize_longitude" takes lon_degrees as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Longitudes are periodic with period 360. A longitude of 270 east is
        the same point as 90 west. Some pipelines emit longitudes outside
        [-180, 180] (e.g. as cumulative bearings); this procedure wraps
        them into the canonical range without changing the represented
        point.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        While lon > 180, subtract 360. While lon < -180, add 360. The
        canonical range is [-180, +180] inclusive at both ends, with -180
        and +180 representing the same antimeridian point.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Loop with at most ceil(|lon|/360) iterations. For well-formed
        input that already lies in [-180, 180] the loop exits immediately.
        For pathological inputs the loop terminates in deterministic time
        proportional to the input magnitude.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Does not allocate or call into any external service.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be lon_degrees
    While result is greater than 180.0:
        Set result to result minus 360.0
    End While
    While result is less than 0.0 minus 180.0:
        Set result to result plus 360.0
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "clamp_latitude" takes lat_degrees as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Latitudes are not periodic - past the pole the direction simply
        reverses. Out-of-range latitudes are therefore clamped to the pole.
        Callers needing to reflect across the pole (with a 180-degree
        longitude flip) should do that themselves; this procedure provides
        only the simple clamp.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        If lat > 90 return 90; if lat < -90 return -90; otherwise return lat.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two compares and one selection. Compiles to a small conditional
        move sequence on x86-64.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If lat_degrees is greater than 90.0:
        Return 90.0
    End If
    If lat_degrees is less than 0.0 minus 90.0:
        Return 0.0 minus 90.0
    End If
    Return lat_degrees
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - Famous reference points (for sanity testing and documentation)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: These are well-known reference points exposed as built-in constants so
Note: that test suites and tutorials can use them without copy-pasting
Note: coordinates from external sources.

Process called "geo_coord_greenwich" returns GeoCoordinate:
    Note: The Royal Observatory at Greenwich, England. Historical origin of
    Note: the IERS Reference Meridian (the modern prime meridian sits about
    Note: 102 m east of the Airy meridian inside the observatory courtyard;
    Note: this constant uses the observatory courtyard convention).
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to 51.4779
    Set c.longitude_degrees to 0.0
    Set c.altitude_meters to 46.0
    Set c.datum_index to 0
    Return c
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_equator_prime_meridian" returns GeoCoordinate:
    Note: The "Null Island" coordinate (0, 0). Used as a sentinel for parser
    Note: failures in many GIS systems. Physically located in the Gulf of
    Note: Guinea about 614 km south of Accra, Ghana.
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to 0.0
    Set c.longitude_degrees to 0.0
    Set c.altitude_meters to 0.0
    Set c.datum_index to 0
    Return c
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_north_pole" returns GeoCoordinate:
    Note: Geographic North Pole. Longitude is undefined at the pole; we use
    Note: 0 by convention.
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to 90.0
    Set c.longitude_degrees to 0.0
    Set c.altitude_meters to 0.0
    Set c.datum_index to 0
    Return c
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_south_pole" returns GeoCoordinate:
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to 0.0 minus 90.0
    Set c.longitude_degrees to 0.0
    Set c.altitude_meters to 0.0
    Set c.datum_index to 0
    Return c
End Process

Process called "geo_coord_everest_summit" returns GeoCoordinate:
    Note: Mt. Everest summit. Elevation per 2020 China-Nepal joint survey:
    Note: 8848.86 m above sea level. Position is from the Nepal Survey
    Note: Department published value.
    Let c be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set c.latitude_degrees to 27.9881
    Set c.longitude_degrees to 86.9250
    Set c.altitude_meters to 8848.86
    Set c.datum_index to 0
    Return c
End Process
